Peel and finely dice the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and finely diced) and chop up the 
@parsley{4}(leaves chopped very finely) very, very finely. Peel the @carrot{2}(peeled 
and cut into chunky little sticks) and chop them into chunky little sticks (as if 
you were going to use them for dipping in hummus). Grate your @parmesan cheese{4}(grated). 
Pre-heat your #grill{} to medium and boil a #pot{} of water.

> Oreganata may sound a bit fussy but it's just a really simple, crunchy topping 
> to take your James Knight Bream to the next level.

Combine the parmesan cheese and parsley (save a pinch of parsley for garnishing). 
Mix in the @dried oregano{2}, garlic and @panko breadcrumbs{4}. Season with a pinch 
of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and grate in the zest of a 1/2 of the @lemon{1}(zested). 
Lastly, add 2 tbsp of lemon juice and mix thoroughly.

Boil your @new potatoes{4} for around ~{12-15%minutes} until you can easily slip a 
knife through them. For the last 5 mins we'll add in the carrots too, but don't worry, 
we'll remind you about them later.

Place your @sea bream fillets{4} on a #baking tray{} and season each fillet with a 
pinch of salt and pepper. Divide the breadcrumb mixture and coat the top of each 
fillet. Place the fillets on the middle/top shelf, underneath the grill and cook 
for around ~{10%minutes}.

> They're ready once the topping goes golden brown.

Here's that reminder: With about ~{5%minutes} to go until the potatoes are cooked, 
put the carrots in the boiling water too.

> If you like them a little more crunchy put them in for 4 mins.

Once they're done, drain the whole pan and keep to the side.

Put the carrots and potatoes in a #mixing bowl{} and gently toss them with a tsp of 
butter if you have some. Sprinkle over a pinch of salt and pepper. Lastly, scatter 
on the pinch of parsley you kept back earlier.

Serve with the cooked fish and devour!